Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Observations:¶

  • order_id and customer_id are integers, and it makes sense because they are numerical variables.
  • restaurant_name and cuisine_type are both objects, and they are categorical variables.
  • cost_of_the_order is a float, and since most payments have decimal values, it is best to keep this column as a float datatype.
  • day_of_the_week is an object and a categorical variable.
  • Although the rating values are numbers, rating is an object datatype because it is seen as a categorical variable in this dataset, and will not be analyzed in a numerical perspective.
  • food_preparation_time and delivery_time are both integers and they are numerical variables, since they are representing the number of minutes.
  • Since non-null count is the same as the number of rows in each column, there are no empty values in this FoodHub dataset.

Observations:¶

  • The sum of null values in each column is equal to 0. There are no missing values in this FoodHub dataset.
  • In the previous .head() function (before question 1), it can be seen that some ratings have a 'Not given' value, which is not necessarily a null value. However, for this situation, taking them as missing values and imputing them with the mode or dropping them can possibly distort the data. It is best to just leave them as they are, and consider them as part of a 'Not given' catergory in the ratings column.

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [34]:
# Write the code here
df1 = df.copy() #created a copy of the df dataframe and stored it in df1
df1['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df1['rating'],errors = 'coerce') #.to_numeric() function in Pandas library changes the ratings column in df1 to numeric values(errors='coerce' changes 'Not Given' values to NaN)
rating_mean = df1.groupby(by=['restaurant_name'])['rating'].mean() #.groupby() function in Pandas used to store mean(.mean() function in Pandas) of df1 ratings values based on restaurant_name in a variable called rating_mean
rating_count = df1.groupby(by=['restaurant_name'])['rating'].count() #.groupby() function in Pandas used to store the count(.count() function in Pandas) of df1 ratings values based on restaurant_name in a variable called rating_count
restaurant_ratings = pd.DataFrame({'Mean': rating_mean, 'Count': rating_count})#.DataFrame() function in Pandas used to create dataframe of outputted values stored in rating_mean and rating_count, labeled as Mean and Count columns
restaurant_ratings[restaurant_ratings['Count'] > 50] #restaurant_ratings dataframe is filtered to only show the rows where count is greater than 50.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [35]:
# Write the code here
df['company_revenue'] = '' #company_revenue column is created in the df dataframe
df['company_revenue'] = np.where(df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20, df['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.25, #using .where() function in NumPy, the first condition is set where 25% charge for orders greater than 20 is added to company_revenue column for each corresponding row
                                np.where(df['cost_of_the_order'] >5, df['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.15,0)) #next condition is set using another .where() function where 15% charge for orders greater than 5 is added to company_revenue column, and if neither condition is met, the company_revenue value for the remaining orders is 0.
df['company_revenue'].sum() #.sum() function in pandas is used to calculate the total value for the company_revenue column
Out[35]:
6166.303

Observations:¶

  • $6,166.30 is the total revenue generated by the company.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • American cuisine has the highest number of orders, followed by Japanese.
  • Middle Eastern, Thai, Southern, French, and Spanish are the least ordered cuisine types, but they have higher cost compared to other cuisine types.
  • Thai and Spanish cuisine types have higher ratings.
  • 736 orders have not been rated.
  • There are more occurences of 5 ratings than 4 or 3. There are no ratings below 3.
  • Rating does not have any pattern with cost, food preparation time, or delivery time.
  • The average food preparation time is 27 minutes, and food preparation time is consistent on both weekends and weekdays.
  • The average delivery time is 24 minutes, and most weekday orders have a higher delivery time than most weekend orders.
  • There are more than double the orders placed on weekends than on weekdays.
  • There are many customers who have only placed one order.
  • The top 5 restaurants are Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop, Blue Ribbon Sushi, Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken, and Parm. The number of orders among all of the restaurants in the dataset differs highly, almost ranging from 200 to less than 10.

Recommendations:¶

  • Since American and Japanese cuisine types are the most popular, in terms of the number of orders placed, incorporating more restaurants that promote these cuisine types can help increase the number of orders placed through FoodHub.
  • Middle Eastern, Thai, Southern, French, and Spanish are not ordered as frequently, however one possible reason can be their higher cost. In terms of ratings, Thai and Spanish have the highest ratings among the cuisine types. Adding more discounts and promotional offers for these cuisine types can possibly encourage more people to try them, and also help achieve higher ratings.
  • On the bright side, 5 is the most frequent rating, and there are no ratings below 3. Unfortunately, 736 orders have not been rated. Offering reinforcements for providing ratings can encourage more customers to give a rating. It can increase the credibility of different restaurants, and also of FoodHub as a whole.
  • More than double the orders are placed on weekends than on weekdays, and most weekday orders have a higher delivery time. This can depend on different factors, such as traffic or work schedules. A higher delivery time does not seem to have any pattern with ratings. Right now, this is not a concern. There can possibly be a pattern between higher delivery time on weekdays and less orders on weekdays. More analysis needs to be done, considering other variables than what is given in this dataset.
  • Offering reinforcements, such as points for orders placed, can encourage customers to keep revisiting the FoodHub app. They are more likely to place more orders.
  • There is a great difference in the number of orders placed among different restaurants. Further analysis on different restaurants and the factors that are possibly contributing to this difference can help understand how some restaurants are getting orders as high as 200, while others have only 10.
